Title:Crisis, institutional innovation and change management: Thoughts from the Greek case 
Abstract:This  article  explores  how  the  current  global  crisis  and  restructuring  of  global capitalism  is related  to  innovation,  in  broad  terms,  and  change  management.  The  aim  is to understand this relation by first presenting a synopsis of the approaches to the crisis of the Greek  socioeconomic  system,  second  focusing  on  the  concept  of  innovation  in  institutional terms,  and  third  examining  the  change  management  mechanisms  that  seem  useful  for  the articulation   of public   economic   policy   in   Stra.Tech.Man   terms   (synthesisof   Strategy-Technology-Management). We suggest that to overcome actual structural crises -such as the Greek  socioeconomic  crisis-the  implementation  and  valorization  of  well  balanced  and effectively implemented sets of institutional innovations is crucial, provided that integrated public policy change management mechanisms are in place. 
